## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never raised — dead code |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.Wait throws AggregateException on fault or cancellation
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Propagate any work exception wrapped in AggregateException
        // (matches original behavior)
        if (task.IsFaulted)
            throw task.Exception!;

        return task.Result;
    }

    // Preferred: async overload
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

1. **No forced termination** — Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If `work` ignores the token, it keeps running after timeout. There is no safe equivalent to `Abort()` in .NET 8.

2. **Fire-and-forget leak** — In the sync version, the `Task.Run` delegate continues executing in the background after timeout. If it holds resources (DB connections, file handles), those stay open.

3. **`Task.Result` vs `task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()`** — Both unwrap `AggregateException` differently. `.Result` wraps in `AggregateException` (matching your original behavior). `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` throws the inner exception directly.

4. **Thread pool starvation** — The original used a dedicated `Thread`. `Task.Run` uses the thread pool. Long-blocking work can starve other tasks. For CPU-heavy work, consider `Task.Factory.StartNew` with `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning`.

### Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Sync (backward-compatible call sites)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ComputeExpensiveThing(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// Async (preferred — pass token into the work so cancellation actually stops it)
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct => await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**Bottom line:** The async overload with `CancellationToken` is the only way to get true cancellation in .NET 8. The sync overload preserves API compatibility but the "abort" semantics are gone — work will complete in the background even after timeout.
